sec.p:
Ginger (
Zingiber officinale Roscoe
) is consumed for health-promoting effects and as a food condiment. Comprehensive phytochemical analysis, other than gingerols and shogaols, has not yet been deeply investigated. Hence, the current research aimed to establish a non-targeted metabolomics approach for the discrimination between fresh ginger rhizome samples collected from four different producing countries, i.e. , China , India , Pakistan , and Peru . In addition, lab-dried samples were analyzed to trace drying-induced metabolites. A comprehensive extraction procedure was carried out resulting in production of polar and non-polar fractions. The polar fraction was analyzed by ultra-performance liquid chromatography coupled with Fourier transform tandem mass spectrometry (UPLC-C 18 -FT-MS/MS) and gas chromatography coupled with time-of-flight mass spectrometry (GC-TOF-MS) post derivatization. UPLC-C 8 -FT-MS/MS was used for analysis of non-polar fraction. Results revealed for identification of a total of 253 metabolites. In addition, multivariate data analysis (MVDA), including principal component analysis (PCA) demonstrated clustering of Asian specimens. Several metabolites with a characteristic pattern for the origin revealing the highest contents of bioactive metabolites in the Peruvian product. Moreover, chemical markers identified, including [6]-gingerol and [6]-shogaol discriminating between fresh and dried samples. Furthermore, abundances of some primary metabolites, including amino acids and cinnamic acid, have confirmed the biosynthetic pathway of gingerols and their transformation upon drying to shogaols. The proposed approach can be applied as a potential candidate for quality assessment of ginger and other medicinal plants.

Plant-derived metabolites represent interesting targets for various scientific fields. Medicinally, secondary metabolites are considered a potential source of novel drugs (

; 

) and used for the treatments of various diseases ranging from simple pain to life-threatening diseases such as cancer (

). Approximately 90% of natural-based medicines are of plant origin (

), which have been supported by the tremendous biodiversity inherent in plant species (

). In addition, herbal medicine is the most popular 
type
worldwide for the primary healthcare services, with 80% of the world population traditionally using it medicinally owing to relative cheapness, safety and acceptability (

). Taxonomically, several recent published articles have used plant metabolites in plant chemotaxonomic classification within relevant species and cultivars (

; 

; 

).

Following the recent advances of hyphenated spectrometric analyses, including gas chromatography coupled with time-of-flight-mass spectrometry (GC-TOF-MS) and ultra-high-performance liquid chromatography coupled with high resolution tandem mass spectrometry (UHPLC-HR-MS/MS), the chemistry of plant metabolites or plant metabolomics have been developed in tremendous steps (

, 2020b). These techniques have gained a special interest in chemotaxonomic classification resolving the complexity of plants metabolome, especially followings its coupling chemometrics tools (

; 

; 

). Moreover, plant metabolomics has important applications in quality control of herbal products ensuring safety, efficacy, and consistency of active principles (

; 

; 

).

Plants of the family 
Zingiberaceae
, including turmeric (

Curcuma longa

L.), ginger (

Zingiber officinale
Roscoe

) and shell ginger (

Alpinia zerumbet
(Pers.) B.L.Burtt & R.M.Sm.

) are commonly used in different communities, due to their attractive food applications and various bioactivities (

). Specifically, ginger, which is used as fresh or dried rhizomes, has been described among Chinese, Ayurvedic and Tibb-Unani herbal medicines. Besides, it is widely-used as spices, nutraceutical, and for the treatment of different gastro-intestinal diseases (
i.e.
, nausea, dysentery, anorexia, diarrhea, flatulence, and cancer), infections, cough, bronchitis, liver dysfunctions, and ageing-related degenerative diseases (

; 

; 

; 

). All of these activities are attributed to its distinctive phytochemical profile, which principally includes phenolic compounds, in addition to lipids, organic acids, volatile terpenoids, and dietary fibers (

; 

; 

; 

). Ginger phenolic compounds are particularly numerous and diverse and include [6]-gingerol, [8]-gingerol, [10]-gingerol, [6]-gingerdiol, [6]-shogaol, [6]-paradol, acetoxy-[10]-gingerol, and gingerenone A. These are the most bioactive secondary metabolites, responsible for ginger aromatic and pungent flavor, bioactivities, and often serve as biomarkers in quality control research (

; 

).

Quality control regulations of herbal products consider several aspects, such as botanical, chemical, biochemical, organoleptic, biological and physical characteristics (

). Previously, single component-based analyses were approved by international pharmacopeias and quality control guidelines, using simple methods, such as TLC, HPLC, and specific tests or simple tandem spectrometric methods for identification, and compositional analysis of medicinal plants (

). However, these are currently inadequate to assess product quality and unable to cover the different aspects of analytical regulations (

). Recently, metabolomics approaches have proven efficiency as a comprehensive tool for analysis of all small molecules (Mw 
<
1500 Da) in an organism, tissue or even single cell at very low concentrations (

; 

, 2020b). Additionally, metabolomics techniques have resulted in fingerprint spectra for herbal products helping in authentication and quality control of herbal medicines (

; 

). High throughput screening and analysis of huge number of samples have added to the advantages of metabolomics application in quality control studies (

; 

).

Metabolomics have been applied previously to evaluate the effect of geographical origin of the same plant species and to discriminate between the different ginger cultivars (

). For instance, ginger samples collected from different geographical origins were discriminated based on gingerols and six other gingerol-related compounds using ultra-performance liquid chromatography equipped with mass spectrometry (UPLC/MS) coupled with chemometrics (

; 

). Additionally, metabolomic-based approach characterized phenolic metabolites of family 
Zingiberaceae
including ginger collected from 
Korea
and 
Ethiopia
(

). These previous studies focused on the determination of gingerols and shogaols as markers for quality assessment owing to their commercial availability. However, a comprehensive analysis of other metabolites of ginger has not yet been deeply investigated.

Principal component analysis (PCA) was conducted on the obtained data matrix of the identified metabolites. PCA, which was conducted on all samples, showed that blank samples were located out beyond the 95% confidence limit, indicating its unique chemical profile, while the quality control (QC) samples were located centrally indicating the robustness of the applied analytical method (
Figure S5
).

Metabolites that contributed significantly to the differentiation between different ginger samples were extracted by using VIP scores as a quantitative estimation of the discriminatory power of each individual metabolite. Overall, the top 25 metabolites with a VIP score greater than 1 were considered location-specific informative metabolite markers (
Fig. 4B
). These metabolites suggest location-specific alterations in gingerols, amino acids and organic acids. Notably, the contents of methyl gingerols and paradols as well as glutathione significantly discriminated Peruvian ginger. Most amino acids such as ornithine and arginine as well as acetoxy gingerdiols discriminated Chinese ginger. Phosphatidylethanolamine (PE) significantly increased in Indian ginger. Organic acids such uric acid and 4-hydroxy-benzoic acid as well as the sugar alcohol erythritol showed the highest level in Pakistani ginger. The group of Peruvian ginger samples showed a dramatic difference to other ginger samples on the HCA dendrogram (
Fig. 4C
). Meanwhile, Chinese and Indian samples clearly clustered from the Pakistani samples.

Peruvian ginger showed the lowest abundances of most amino acids, in comparison with the Asian samples (
Fig. 6
). Additionally, several glactolipid classes such as monogalactosyldiacylglycerol (MGDG), digalactosyl diacylglycerol (DGDG) and sulfoquinovosyl diacylglycerols (SQDG) as well as phospholipids such as phosphatidylcholines (PC), phosphatidylglycerol (PG), phosphatidylinositol (PI), and phosphatidylserine (PS) showed a reversed pattern from the amino acids. These lipid classes showed the highest abundances in Peruvian ginger, while the Asian samples showed lower abundances (
Figure S7
). On the other hand, free fatty acids levels did not change between the tested fresh samples. Other metabolites such as starch, benzoic acid, riboflavin, and glutathione were more abundant in the Peruvian samples (
Fig. 6
and S 
8
).

Moreover, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) classifies ginger among âgenerally recognized as safeâ (GRAS) materials or substances (
). Identification and quality assessment of ginger is based on few componentsâ determination, including gingerols, gingerdiones and shogaols contents by simple chromatographic techniques, as TLC and liquid chromatography equipped with UV detector (
). Also, adulteration of ginger powder is rare owing to its characteristic aroma, however, in older literature, various species of
Curcuma
,
Capsicum
, and grains of Paradise (
Amomum melegueta
) may be added to exhausted material in order to enhance color and pungency. Addition of plant starch derived from other species was also reported (USP41, 2018).

PCA analysis is a powerful tool usually used to handle a large amount of data based on multiple variables. It allowed the separation of the analyzed samples based on the geographical closeness of the countries of origin. PCA showed clear separation of geographically different ginger samples. In addition, OPLS-DA showed clear separation of fresh and dried counterparts. Different markers were chosen to justify the differences. Examples include [6]-gingerol, [6]-shogaol, and [6]-gingerdiol 5- 

O
-Î²

- 
D-
glucopyranoside. Transformation of [6]-gingerol to [6]-shogaol upon drying was consistent with the previously-reported results showing that dried ginger is more effective and widely-used for therapeutic applications than the fresh counterpart due to high content and abundance of [6]-shogaol (

; 

; 

). Interestingly, [6]-shogaol is known for its pharmacological activities as potential antioxidant, and anti-inflammatory even more than gingerols (

).

Interestingly, consumption of ginger as a functional food was proven in the current research, where presence of high levels of citric acid added to the value of ginger as nutraceutical since citric acid has been reported to possess neuro-, hepato-, and geno-protective activities (Abdel-Salam et al., 2014). Other acids, such as 2-hydroxy cinnamic acid or 
O
-coumaric acid seemed to be among the heat-induced products and contributed to the antioxidant power of the dried ginger preparations. Additionally, assessment of amino acids and organic acids profiles are important parameters for food and herbal quality control (

; 

). Among the detected amino acids, valine content was rich in dried than fresh samples in general. This could be explained by the resistance of branched chain amino acids against heat and potentially also the conversion of other branched chain amino acids such as isoleucine to the simplest branched chain amino acid valine. Other primary metabolites such as xylose, riboflavin and glutathione were more abundant in fresh samples than dried products. This also confirmed that fresh samples may be considered a more nutritive source of valuable elements than dried products.

Ginger rhizomes have been widely used in modern medicine due the promising biological activities attributed to the homologous phenolic ketones gingerols, particularly [6]-gingerol and its derivatives (

). Shogaols, the dehydrated forms of gingerols, are thought to be derived from the thermal processing (e.g. drying or heating), or long term storage of gingerols (

). Intriguingly, shogaols are more pungent and more potent than gingerols as antioxidant, anti-inflammatory and chemopreventive (

). Our results revealed the presence of minor amounts of shogaol in the fresh ginger samples, which were increased several folds upon drying. Based on these results, we suggest the usage of fresh ginger as a nutritive food and dry ginger in modern medicine. Drying of herbs removes excess moisture and hence extends their shelf lives, reducing their spoilage and minimizing economic loss to farmers (

). Furthermore, the estimation of the dosage used of some phytochemicals and their products can be more easily controlled from dried herbs than in fresh state. However, the shelf-life of ginger rhizomes is short, making the drying is essential for optimal storability.

The current study has also succeeded to highlight biosynthetic aspects of ginger major metabolites, including gingerol biosynthesis. Previous studies have confirmed that [6]-gingerol is biosynthesized through the phenylpropanoid pathway or specifically shikimate-acetate mixed pathway (Figure S15). Firstly, Denniff, et al. demonstrated that dihydroferulic acid and hexanoic acid were the key intermediates in biosynthesis of [6]-gingerol. However, later Ramirez-Ahumada et al. have proposed an alternative pathway. This study showed that other key intermediates were involved as p -coumaroyl 5- O -shikimate and 1-dehydro-[6]-gingerdione (
). Abundances pattern of phenylalanine and cinnamic acids confirmed that gingerols are biosynthesized via shikimic acid pathway. Moreover, an inverse relationship was observed between the abundance of the [6]-gingerol precursors, i.e. , phenyl alanine and cinnamic acid, and end products, i.e. , [6]-gingerol, gingerenone A, and gingerenone B, especially in fresh samples, where samples with low precursor contents showed high levels of [6]-gingerol. Similarly, hexahydrocurcumin was highly affected by the same precursors and demonstrated to be synthesized also from phenylalanine and cinnamic acid via a side reaction with feruloyl-CoA parallel to biosynthesis of [6]-gingerol. This pathway was also consistent with previous studies (
). However, its conversion to gingerenone A and gingerenone B was not equally produced, especially for the Chinese sample, where conversion to gingerenone B was more favored.

For protein extraction, the washed pellet remained after metabolite extraction was re-suspended in 150 Î¼L of protein extraction buffer (6 M urea, 2 M thiourea, 15 mM DTT, 2% CHAPS and protease and phosphatase inhibitors). The samples were incubated for 30 min on an orbital shaker (100 rpm) at room temperature and finally centrifuged at 5000Ã g for 10 min and the protein concentration was determined from the collected supernatant (
). For starch extraction, the washed pellet after protein extraction was re-dissolved in 0.5 mL of water and the samples were heated at 100 â¦ C for 1.5 h. The dissolved starch was digested enzymatically using a mix of Î± -amyloglucosidase and Î± -amylase, according to manufacturer instructions. Starch concentration was determined based on a calibration curve of a standard glucose (
).

For UPLC/MS data, it is often difficult to fully identify compounds without having commercially available authentic standards. Owing to the non-availability of authentic standards for gingerol-related compounds, as well as other ginger metabolites, annotation of the detected metabolite features from UPLC/MS metabolomics approach was based on accurate 
m/z
, retention time, isotope distribution and fragmentation pattern (

; 

). The metabolite information was searched against public databases (METLIN, Chem-Spider, KEGG, PubChem, MassBank, HMDB, KNApSAcK, Metabolomics. jp, Metabolomics workbench). Some compounds such as gingerols and shogaols were identified based on comparison with commercially available standards. Metabolite features from positive and negative ionization modes were merged into one dataset (CalderÂ´on-Santiago et al., 2016). Metabolite features that are derived from the same compound were grouped based on 5 ppm tolerance of the mass difference, 0.05 min tolerance of retention time and
>
0.9 correlation coefficient between the metabolite features across all the samples. For GC-MS data analysis, chromatograms were exported from LecoÂ® ChromaTOF-GC Software v3.34 to R software (www.r-project.org). Peak detection, retention time alignment and library matching were performed using the Target Search R package (

).

In addition, MVDA such as principal component analysis (PCA) was conducted to evaluate the obtained results and to exclude outliers. Also, orthogonal projections to latent structures discriminant analysis (OPLS-DA) was applied to determine several markers that are distinct in dried samples. Furthermore, variable importance in the projection (VIP) scores, which is an estimation of the importance of each variable in the projection used PLS-DA. Variables with a VIP score of â¥1 were considered important. VIP scores were extracted for components 1 and 2 since they accounted for about 80% of the total variance. MVDA was performed using SIMCA-P Version 13.0 (Umetrics, UmeÃ¥, 
Sweden
) and Metaboanalyst 3.0 (

), following log 
2
-transformation and Pareto scaling (centered mean is divided by the square root of the SD of each variable).
